The paper presents a logical framework for representing and reasoning about preferences, which is a topic that falls under artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The use of fuzzy answer set programming suggests that the paper may also be relevant to logic in computer science (cs.LO) and data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). Additionally, the application of the framework to course scheduling suggests that the paper may be relevant to programming languages (cs.PL) and software engineering (cs.SE).
